{{italic title}} {{Infobox book | name = Field Guide to the Birds of Australia | title_orig = The Birds of Australia – a Book of Identification | translator = | image = Field Guide to the Birds of Australia (Simpson & Day).jpg | caption = | author = [[Ken Simpson]] | illustrator = [[Nicolas Day]] | cover_artist = Nicolas Day | country = Australia | language = English | series = | subject = Australian birds | genre = [[Field guide]] | publisher = Lloyd O’Neil: Melbourne | pub_date = 1984 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print (hardback) | pages = 352 | isbn = 0-85550-492-7 | oclc = | dewey = 598.2994 | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
The Simpson & Day '''''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''''' is one of the main national bird [[field guide]]s used by Australian [[birdwatching|birders]], which over the years has evolved through several revised and updated editions. Total sales exceed 500,000 copies.<ref name=pb>Penguin Books.</ref>
==History== The book was first published in 1984 by Lloyd O’Neil as ''The Birds of Australia'', in [[hardcover]] format with a [[dust jacket]], 285&nbsp;mm high by 215&nbsp;mm wide and weighing 1.7&nbsp;kg. It contained illustrations by [[Nicolas Day]] of 758 species on 128 colour plates. It was divided into three main sections, a key to bird [[family (biology)|families]], the field information section with the plates opposite the relevant species descriptions and distribution maps, and the “handbook” with more detailed information on avian biology. The [[endpaper]]s featured life-size profile drawings of the [[beak|bills]] of [[albatross]]es and [[petrel]]s to aid the identification of beach-washed [[seabird]]s.<ref name=s&d>Simpson & Day (1984).</ref>
Although the dust jacket and [[title page]] featured Ken Simpson and Nicolas Day as coauthors, the [[Acknowledgment (creative arts)|acknowledgements]] principally credited Ken Simpson as Editor, Nicolas Day as Illustrator and [[Peter Trusler]] as Art Director, with several others credited as writers, contributing illustrators and in other capacities.<ref name=s&d/>
Subsequent editions were published by [[Penguin Books|Penguin Australia]] under the Viking imprint in a smaller size (220&nbsp;mm high by 160&nbsp;mm wide and only half the weight), with a flexible, waterproof, plastic cover suitable for use as a field guide, and renamed the ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Additional developments were a rare bird bulletin section to cover vagrant and newly recorded species and to encourage users to report sightings of rarities, and the inclusion of [[checklist]]s for Australia’s outlying islands and external territories. From the seventh edition the handbook section was dropped and the rare bird bulletin extended.<ref name=pb/>
===Editions=== * 1st - 1984 * 2nd - 1986 * 3rd - 1989 * 4th - 1993 * 5th - 1996 * 6th - 1999 * 7th - 2004 * 8th - 2010
