{{refimprove|date=February 2012}} {{Infobox person |name = Manuel Dias |image = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1574 |birth_place = [[Castelo Branco, Portugal|Castelo Branco]], [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]] |death_date = 4 March 1659 |death_place = China |nationality = [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] |occupation = Jesuit missionary |known_for = Introduction of the telescope in China |signature = }}
'''Manuel Dias the Younger''' (1574{{nbsp}}– 4 March 1659)<ref>{{citation |first=João Manuel |last=Esteves Pereira |author2=Guilherme Rodrigues |display-authors=1 |title=Diccionario Historico, Chorographico, Heraldico, Biographico, Bibliographico, Numismatico, e Artistico... |publisher=J. Romano Torres |date=1907 }}. {{pt icon}}</ref> was a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[Jesuit China missions|Jesuit missionary]].
==Name== Manuel Dias the Younger ({{lang-la|Junior}}) acquired his epithet to distinguish him from [[Manuel Dias the Elder]] ({{c.|1561}}–1639).{{sfnp|Jami & al.|2008|p=99}} He is also known as '''Emanuel''' or '''Emmanuel Diaz'''. His name was [[transcription into Chinese characters|sinified]] as '''Yang Manuo''' ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|陽|瑪|諾}}}}), and he was also referred to by his [[courtesy name]] '''Yanxi''' (演西).
{{anchor|Biography|History}}
==Life== Dias arrived in China in 1610, reaching Beijing in 1613. He introduced the [[telescope]] into [[China]] just a few years after it had been developed in the Netherlands (1608). The telescope was first mentioned in his ''Tian Wen Lüe'' (''Explicatio Sphaerae Coelestis'') in 1615.<ref name="needham volume 3 444">Needham, Volume 3, 444.</ref> In the ''Tian Wen Lüe'' he presented the latest European [[astronomy|astronomical]] knowledge in the form of questions and answers. The book was studied and published until the 19th century.
==See also== * [[Wenceslas Pantaleon Kirwitzer]]
